http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/automobiles/autoreviews/13BLOCK.html?ex=1336708800&en=d217d80ebce62267&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	Review - Lincoln MKX - Test Drive - New York Times MKX: Beyond the Edge Ford&#146;s American luxury division finally gets a crossover wagon. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 13, 2007 WHILE Cadillac has staged a respectable revival of late, times are still tough for Lincoln, the other venerable American luxury line. Skip to next paragraph The X Files: Four Luxury Crossovers Lincoln had its last bona fide hit, the Navigator sport utility, nearly a decade ago. In the years since, it has posted a lineup that could confirm the existence of chaos theory. The bizarre Blackwood pickup for 2002 was dead on arrival — appropriate, since it came only in black and featured what appeared to be a powered coffin lid over a carpeted bed. Failing to take the hint, Lincoln brought out another luxury pickup, the Mark LT, which has also underperformed in the showroom. On the sport utility front, Lincoln cobbled together the Aviator for 2002. It was basically a Ford Explorer with a deluxe interior, but at a price above $45,000, few left the hangar. Beyond its price, the Aviator’s failing — and Lincoln’s, too — was to miss the crossover wave. Models like the Lexus RX, now the perennial top seller among luxury sport utilities, were really cars underneath. By and large, Americans have discovered in recent years that they prefer crossovers to truck-centric models like the Aviator. Better late than never, Lincoln now paddles in with its first crossover: the MKX, not to be confused with Acura’s competing MDX — or with Lincoln’s own MKZ, a sedan formerly known as the Zephyr, or its yet-to-come MKS. (Chaos also rules the Lincoln’s naming department.) Based on the Ford Edge and Mazda CX-9, the five-passenger MKX is vastly more flightworthy than the Aviator. It is competent and quite striking. It starts at $36,445 including optional all-wheel drive, far less than other luxury models of its size: about $3,000 below the Lexus RX 350, about $4,000 less than the Acura, about $7,000 below a Mercedes ML350. But let’s be honest. The MKX may impress price shoppers and Lincoln loyalists, or people who remember where they were when Barry Goldwater got the Republican nomination. But it is less likely to impress people who have forged lasting relationships with rich foreigners, like the sport wagons from Lexus, Mercedes and BMW. No doubt, the Lincoln wins some style points: The MKX has an aerodynamic shape that even the Jetsons might like, and a wall-to-wall chrome grille that adds some visual sizzle. It’s a handsome ride. The interior is reasonably comfortable, though the front seats were handicapped by a short, hard bottom cushion. A central touch screen smoothly controls the audio system, navigation unit and other functions. (Lincoln could teach BMW and Mercedes a thing or two about user-friendly electronics.) An enormous sunroof is part of a $4,795 package that includes the navigation system, satellite radio and THX audio system. The MKX’s sharply angled windshield resulted in distracting reflections from vents atop the dashboard. But the gauges may be the biggest faux pas; did anyone at Lincoln notice how cheap they look? They’re penciled in a wispy, almost girlish font that recalls a J. C. Penney circular. The Lincoln’s neatest feature may be the dual buttons in the hatch area that drop the split 60-40 rear seats flat in a one-finger operation. There is useful storage back there, though the stylishly sloping roof reduces the ultimate capacity: both the Acura and Lexus have about 20 percent more space with the rear seats folded. On the road, the MKX is smooth, solid and quiet. But it drives like, well, a nice minivan, and I’d wager that a Honda Odyssey could beat it around a road course. Of course, the MKX is a prettified Ford Edge, and like that crossover wagon it feels rather large and unwieldy. Compared with the Ford, the Lincoln’s suspension is biased toward a comfortable ride, so it is tuned like a baby’s mashed potatoes: soft, messy and poorly controlled. The steering traces the right path, but the feel is vague and muffled. The 3.5-liter V-6, the new go-to engine for multiple Ford models, puts out a healthy 265 horsepower and 250 pound-feet of maximum torque. The six-speed automatic transmission is decently smooth, though the lack of manual-shift ability is another clue to the Lincoln’s easy-cruising intentions. The MKX also tips the scales at 4,420 pounds, one reason for a somewhat leisurely 8.1-second run from a standstill to 60 m.p.h. Yet despite the mass, the federal fuel economy rating is an impressive 17 miles a gallon in town, 24 on the highway, with all-wheel drive. (Front-drive models are rated 1 m.p.g. higher in town and country.) Braking is less impressive, though, as proved in testing by Car and Driver. The magazine recorded a 197-foot stop from 70 m.p.h., near the bottom in the class. The Lincoln weighs about 100 pounds less than the longer, wider Acura, and 300 less than a Mercedes M-Class. But the Acura, with its terrific suspension and performance-tuned all-wheel-drive system, feels like a nimble sport sedan in comparison — without any tradeoffs in ride or roominess. The Acura isn’t the only one: a homegrown rival, the Cadillac SRX, pioneered an adaptive magnetically controlled suspension that has been adopted by super sports cars like the Chevrolet Corvette, Ferrari 599 GTB and Audi R8. As you might expect, the Cadillac outhandles the Lincoln. In the MKX’s defense, the Lexus RX is no barn burner, either. And again, the Lincoln undercuts the competition: stuffed with options, my test car checked in at $43,890. Skeptics will note that the Lincoln’s stablemate, the Ford Edge, has a base price about $8,800 lower. They may well dismiss the Lincoln as an overpriced Ford. But people who love the Lincoln’s looks, and value smoothness over sport, may prefer to call the MKX a bargain Lexus. Next Article in Automobiles (2 of 41) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Campaign Briefing | Recalls: An Alert For Agent Cool Blue Toyota Deepens Discounts on Its New Pickup With Top-Selling Silverado, G.M. Sales Defied Trend and Rose for Month BEHIND THE WHEEL/2007 Ford Edge; More Weighty Than Edgy Utility Vehicles and Other Light Trucks Next Article in Automobiles (2 of 41) &#x00bb; The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny The Curious Cook: The Five-Second Rule Explored, or How Dirty Is That Bologna? The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks Highway Debris, Long an Eyesore, Grows as Hazard New York City Renters Cope With Squeeze Psychiatrists, Children and Drug Industry&#8217;s Role The Critical Years: Middle School Manages Distractions of Adolescence Genes Take Charge, and Diets Fall by the Wayside Fisher Is a Father First, and a Jazz Player Later Your Money: A Contrarian on Retirement Says Wait Go to Complete List » Giuliani to Support Abortion Rights G.O.P. Moderates Warn Bush Iraq Must Show Gains Bush in Accord With Democrats on Trade Deals President Open to Benchmarks in Iraq Measure Gonzales Seems Confident He Will Stay, Officials Say Facebook to Offer Free Classifieds Role of F.B.I. Informer Draws Praise and Questions On Carrier in Gulf, Cheney Issues Warning to Iran Romney Works to Put Skeptics' Doubts to Rest Go to Complete List » Go to Complete List » The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/automobiles/autoreviews/13BLOCK.html?ex=1336708800&en=d217d80ebce62267&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	Review - Lincoln MKX - Test Drive - New York Times MKX: Beyond the Edge Ford&#146;s American luxury division finally gets a crossover wagon. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 13, 2007 WHILE Cadillac has staged a respectable revival of late, times are still tough for Lincoln, the other venerable American luxury line. Skip to next paragraph The X Files: Four Luxury Crossovers Lincoln had its last bona fide hit, the Navigator sport utility, nearly a decade ago. In the years since, it has posted a lineup that could confirm the existence of chaos theory. The bizarre Blackwood pickup for 2002 was dead on arrival — appropriate, since it came only in black and featured what appeared to be a powered coffin lid over a carpeted bed. Failing to take the hint, Lincoln brought out another luxury pickup, the Mark LT, which has also underperformed in the showroom. On the sport utility front, Lincoln cobbled together the Aviator for 2002. It was basically a Ford Explorer with a deluxe interior, but at a price above $45,000, few left the hangar. Beyond its price, the Aviator’s failing — and Lincoln’s, too — was to miss the crossover wave. Models like the Lexus RX, now the perennial top seller among luxury sport utilities, were really cars underneath. By and large, Americans have discovered in recent years that they prefer crossovers to truck-centric models like the Aviator. Better late than never, Lincoln now paddles in with its first crossover: the MKX, not to be confused with Acura’s competing MDX — or with Lincoln’s own MKZ, a sedan formerly known as the Zephyr, or its yet-to-come MKS. (Chaos also rules the Lincoln’s naming department.) Based on the Ford Edge and Mazda CX-9, the five-passenger MKX is vastly more flightworthy than the Aviator. It is competent and quite striking. It starts at $36,445 including optional all-wheel drive, far less than other luxury models of its size: about $3,000 below the Lexus RX 350, about $4,000 less than the Acura, about $7,000 below a Mercedes ML350. But let’s be honest. The MKX may impress price shoppers and Lincoln loyalists, or people who remember where they were when Barry Goldwater got the Republican nomination. But it is less likely to impress people who have forged lasting relationships with rich foreigners, like the sport wagons from Lexus, Mercedes and BMW. No doubt, the Lincoln wins some style points: The MKX has an aerodynamic shape that even the Jetsons might like, and a wall-to-wall chrome grille that adds some visual sizzle. It’s a handsome ride. The interior is reasonably comfortable, though the front seats were handicapped by a short, hard bottom cushion. A central touch screen smoothly controls the audio system, navigation unit and other functions. (Lincoln could teach BMW and Mercedes a thing or two about user-friendly electronics.) An enormous sunroof is part of a $4,795 package that includes the navigation system, satellite radio and THX audio system. The MKX’s sharply angled windshield resulted in distracting reflections from vents atop the dashboard. But the gauges may be the biggest faux pas; did anyone at Lincoln notice how cheap they look? They’re penciled in a wispy, almost girlish font that recalls a J. C. Penney circular. The Lincoln’s neatest feature may be the dual buttons in the hatch area that drop the split 60-40 rear seats flat in a one-finger operation. There is useful storage back there, though the stylishly sloping roof reduces the ultimate capacity: both the Acura and Lexus have about 20 percent more space with the rear seats folded. On the road, the MKX is smooth, solid and quiet. But it drives like, well, a nice minivan, and I’d wager that a Honda Odyssey could beat it around a road course. Of course, the MKX is a prettified Ford Edge, and like that crossover wagon it feels rather large and unwieldy. Compared with the Ford, the Lincoln’s suspension is biased toward a comfortable ride, so it is tuned like a baby’s mashed potatoes: soft, messy and poorly controlled. The steering traces the right path, but the feel is vague and muffled. The 3.5-liter V-6, the new go-to engine for multiple Ford models, puts out a healthy 265 horsepower and 250 pound-feet of maximum torque. The six-speed automatic transmission is decently smooth, though the lack of manual-shift ability is another clue to the Lincoln’s easy-cruising intentions. The MKX also tips the scales at 4,420 pounds, one reason for a somewhat leisurely 8.1-second run from a standstill to 60 m.p.h. Yet despite the mass, the federal fuel economy rating is an impressive 17 miles a gallon in town, 24 on the highway, with all-wheel drive. (Front-drive models are rated 1 m.p.g. higher in town and country.) Braking is less impressive, though, as proved in testing by Car and Driver. The magazine recorded a 197-foot stop from 70 m.p.h., near the bottom in the class. The Lincoln weighs about 100 pounds less than the longer, wider Acura, and 300 less than a Mercedes M-Class. But the Acura, with its terrific suspension and performance-tuned all-wheel-drive system, feels like a nimble sport sedan in comparison — without any tradeoffs in ride or roominess. The Acura isn’t the only one: a homegrown rival, the Cadillac SRX, pioneered an adaptive magnetically controlled suspension that has been adopted by super sports cars like the Chevrolet Corvette, Ferrari 599 GTB and Audi R8. As you might expect, the Cadillac outhandles the Lincoln. In the MKX’s defense, the Lexus RX is no barn burner, either. And again, the Lincoln undercuts the competition: stuffed with options, my test car checked in at $43,890. Skeptics will note that the Lincoln’s stablemate, the Ford Edge, has a base price about $8,800 lower. They may well dismiss the Lincoln as an overpriced Ford. But people who love the Lincoln’s looks, and value smoothness over sport, may prefer to call the MKX a bargain Lexus. Next Article in Automobiles (2 of 41) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Campaign Briefing | Recalls: An Alert For Agent Cool Blue Toyota Deepens Discounts on Its New Pickup With Top-Selling Silverado, G.M. Sales Defied Trend and Rose for Month BEHIND THE WHEEL/2007 Ford Edge; More Weighty Than Edgy Utility Vehicles and Other Light Trucks Next Article in Automobiles (2 of 41) &#x00bb; The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny The Curious Cook: The Five-Second Rule Explored, or How Dirty Is That Bologna? The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks Highway Debris, Long an Eyesore, Grows as Hazard New York City Renters Cope With Squeeze Psychiatrists, Children and Drug Industry&#8217;s Role The Critical Years: Middle School Manages Distractions of Adolescence Genes Take Charge, and Diets Fall by the Wayside Fisher Is a Father First, and a Jazz Player Later Your Money: A Contrarian on Retirement Says Wait Go to Complete List » Giuliani to Support Abortion Rights G.O.P. Moderates Warn Bush Iraq Must Show Gains Bush in Accord With Democrats on Trade Deals President Open to Benchmarks in Iraq Measure Gonzales Seems Confident He Will Stay, Officials Say Facebook to Offer Free Classifieds Role of F.B.I. Informer Draws Praise and Questions On Carrier in Gulf, Cheney Issues Warning to Iran Romney Works to Put Skeptics' Doubts to Rest Go to Complete List » Go to Complete List » The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/15/automobiles/15TRAILER.html?ex=1334289600&en=a942d14ad900aae7&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	Airstream: The Concept Travels Well - New York Times Airstream: The Concept Travels Well The classic Airstream trailer still appeals to a nation of rolling stones. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: April 15, 2007 AS if abandoned by a misdirected camper who parked in the dark, a silver Airstream trailer sits these days in the lobby of the Museum of Modern Art. A model called the Bambi, designed in 1960 with Airstream&#8217;s distinctive streamlined riveted skin, has been acquired for the museum&#8217;s design collection. Skip to next paragraph Keeping The Shiny Side Up The first Airstream, the Clipper, arrived in 1936 amid a national craze for streamlining &#151; in cars, in buildings, in toasters &#151; as the brainchild of an inventor and travel promoter named Wally Byam. After World War II, as the highway system expanded, the economy boomed and Airstreams gained starring roles in Hollywood films, the trailer came to symbolize American-style travel. Airstream&#8217;s appeal seems to have few limits, and indeed a powerful world traveler recently provided proof of its persistent appeal. On a trip to Asia in February, Vice President traveled in an Airstream &#151; inside an airplane. Mark Silva, chief of the Washington bureau of The Chicago Tribune, accompanied the vice president as the press corps&#8217; pool print reporter. The group flew on a huge gray C-17 cargo plane that the Air Force calls the Spirit of , in honor of the late senator. Mr. Silva said that when he boarded he noted the familiar outline of the Airstream roof inside the vast fuselage. &#8220;I crawled on the floor to look at the nameplate,&#8221; Mr. Silva said, confirming that it read &#8220;Airstream, Jackson Center, Ohio.&#8221; Inside, Mr. Silva said in an interview, &#8220;there were plush leather chairs, blue-gray carpet, wood paneling, recessed lighting and a TV and DVD player.&#8221; He said the Airstream reminded him of one of the first he had seen, on the cover of a Ry Cooder record album from 1970. &#8220;The Airstream is the symbol of taking it on the road with style,&#8221; he added. A home for the road, the Airstream has long intrigued Americans as an ideal combination of their twin loves, vehicle and home. Its functionalism also let it be read as a symbol of the ideals of modern architecture. Christian Larsen, a curatorial assistant in &#8217;s department of architecture and design, said, &#8220;The Bambi is a machine for living and traveling, the sort of industrialized, rationalized vessel that had long been the dream object of modernist architects, from Le Corbusier to Buckminster Fuller.&#8221; Mr. Larsen also related the Airstream to the work of artists like Andrea Zittel, who builds trailerlike works, installed in galleries or outdoor installations. In recent years, the Airstream has attracted the attention of automakers, too. Nissan Design America, the California studio of the Japanese automaker, produced an Airstream trailer concept displayed at auto shows after its introduction at the New York International Contemporary Furniture Fair in 2003. Bryan Thompson, one of the designers, said Nissan&#8217;s work with Airstream led to the BaseCamp, a $20,000 trailer with a pop-up Kelty tent. The BaseCamp, which is now sold by Airstream, is light enough to be towed by the average car. &#8220;Airstream is one of those companies that is part of the heart and soul of American design,&#8221; Mr. Thompson said. &#8220;The shape is timeless, the materials are modern and the fabrication is hands-on traditional. They have the ability to combine Old World handmade craftsmanship with cutting-edge technology.&#8221; More recently, Airstream, which is based in Jackson Center, Ohio, and now owned by Thor Industries, has collaborated with Ford. The automaker&#8217;s Airstream design study, a crossover wagon theoretically powered by hydrogen fuel cells, was unveiled in Detroit in January and has been on display at the New York auto show, which closes today. The alliance grew out of a high-concept future study ordered by J Mays, the group vice president for design at Ford, to explore the American journey. The result was a concept vehicle of gleaming aluminum and orange window frames aimed at the growing number of baby boomers who are 55 and older &#151; a group that has historically accounted for a large percentage of trailer buyers. &#8220;The Ford Airstream concept captures the sense of optimism and adventure conveyed in American aircraft, spacecraft and the streamlined shape of Airstream trailers,&#8221; Mr. Mays said. The Ford concept realizes Wally Byam&#8217;s dream of eventually making the Airstream a self-propelled land yacht. (He foresaw a motorized portion that would detach from the mothership, like a dinghy.) It recalls the VW Microbus, and for that matter the Stout Scarab, a 1935 precursor to the minivan. Inside, the Ford concept car shifts its frame of reference to more distant travel. The materials and colors &#151; called &#8220;cosmic red and white&#8221; &#151; were inspired by the spacecraft in the 1968 film &#8220;2001: A Space Odyssey.&#8221; Space buffs will recall another connection between space travel and Airstream. In 1969, upon their return from the moon, the Apollo 11 astronauts were quartered inside a modified Airstream called the mobile quarantine facility. They remained in the silver pod for three weeks; President visited and waved at the astronauts through the window. Next Article in Automobiles (40 of 41) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Find New Cars » Find Used Cars » Explore Collectible Cars » Sell Your Car » The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny T