http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/automobiles/autoreviews/13BLOCK.html	Review - Lincoln MKX - Test Drive - New York Times MKX: Beyond the Edge Ford&#146;s American luxury division finally gets a crossover wagon. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 13, 2007 WHILE Cadillac has staged a respectable revival of late, times are still tough for Lincoln, the other venerable American luxury line. Skip to next paragraph The X Files: Four Luxury Crossovers Lincoln had its last bona fide hit, the Navigator sport utility, nearly a decade ago. In the years since, it has posted a lineup that could confirm the existence of chaos theory. The bizarre Blackwood pickup for 2002 was dead on arrival — appropriate, since it came only in black and featured what appeared to be a powered coffin lid over a carpeted bed. Failing to take the hint, Lincoln brought out another luxury pickup, the Mark LT, which has also underperformed in the showroom. On the sport utility front, Lincoln cobbled together the Aviator for 2002. It was basically a Ford Explorer with a deluxe interior, but at a price above $45,000, few left the hangar. Beyond its price, the Aviator’s failing — and Lincoln’s, too — was to miss the crossover wave. Models like the Lexus RX, now the perennial top seller among luxury sport utilities, were really cars underneath. By and large, Americans have discovered in recent years that they prefer crossovers to truck-centric models like the Aviator. Better late than never, Lincoln now paddles in with its first crossover: the MKX, not to be confused with Acura’s competing MDX — or with Lincoln’s own MKZ, a sedan formerly known as the Zephyr, or its yet-to-come MKS. (Chaos also rules the Lincoln’s naming department.) Based on the Ford Edge and Mazda CX-9, the five-passenger MKX is vastly more flightworthy than the Aviator. It is competent and quite striking. It starts at $36,445 including optional all-wheel drive, far less than other luxury models of its size: about $3,000 below the Lexus RX 350, about $4,000 less than the Acura, about $7,000 below a Mercedes ML350. But let’s be honest. The MKX may impress price shoppers and Lincoln loyalists, or people who remember where they were when Barry Goldwater got the Republican nomination. But it is less likely to impress people who have forged lasting relationships with rich foreigners, like the sport wagons from Lexus, Mercedes and BMW. No doubt, the Lincoln wins some style points: The MKX has an aerodynamic shape that even the Jetsons might like, and a wall-to-wall chrome grille that adds some visual sizzle. It’s a handsome ride. The interior is reasonably comfortable, though the front seats were handicapped by a short, hard bottom cushion. A central touch screen smoothly controls the audio system, navigation unit and other functions. (Lincoln could teach BMW and Mercedes a thing or two about user-friendly electronics.) An enormous sunroof is part of a $4,795 package that includes the navigation system, satellite radio and THX audio system. The MKX’s sharply angled windshield resulted in distracting reflections from vents atop the dashboard. But the gauges may be the biggest faux pas; did anyone at Lincoln notice how cheap they look? They’re penciled in a wispy, almost girlish font that recalls a J. C. Penney circular. The Lincoln’s neatest feature may be the dual buttons in the hatch area that drop the split 60-40 rear seats flat in a one-finger operation. There is useful storage back there, though the stylishly sloping roof reduces the ultimate capacity: both the Acura and Lexus have about 20 percent more space with the rear seats folded. On the road, the MKX is smooth, solid and quiet. But it drives like, well, a nice minivan, and I’d wager that a Honda Odyssey could beat it around a road course. Of course, the MKX is a prettified Ford Edge, and like that crossover wagon it feels rather large and unwieldy. Compared with the Ford, the Lincoln’s suspension is biased toward a comfortable ride, so it is tuned like a baby’s mashed potatoes: soft, messy and poorly controlled. The steering traces the right path, but the feel is vague and muffled. The 3.5-liter V-6, the new go-to engine for multiple Ford models, puts out a healthy 265 horsepower and 250 pound-feet of maximum torque. The six-speed automatic transmission is decently smooth, though the lack of manual-shift ability is another clue to the Lincoln’s easy-cruising intentions. The MKX also tips the scales at 4,420 pounds, one reason for a somewhat leisurely 8.1-second run from a standstill to 60 m.p.h. Yet despite the mass, the federal fuel economy rating is an impressive 17 miles a gallon in town, 24 on the highway, with all-wheel drive. (Front-drive models are rated 1 m.p.g. higher in town and country.) Braking is less impressive, though, as proved in testing by Car and Driver. The magazine recorded a 197-foot stop from 70 m.p.h., near the bottom in the class. The Lincoln weighs about 100 pounds less than the longer, wider Acura, and 300 less than a Mercedes M-Class. But the Acura, with its terrific suspension and performance-tuned all-wheel-drive system, feels like a nimble sport sedan in comparison — without any tradeoffs in ride or roominess. The Acura isn’t the only one: a homegrown rival, the Cadillac SRX, pioneered an adaptive magnetically controlled suspension that has been adopted by super sports cars like the Chevrolet Corvette, Ferrari 599 GTB and Audi R8. As you might expect, the Cadillac outhandles the Lincoln. In the MKX’s defense, the Lexus RX is no barn burner, either. And again, the Lincoln undercuts the competition: stuffed with options, my test car checked in at $43,890. Skeptics will note that the Lincoln’s stablemate, the Ford Edge, has a base price about $8,800 lower. They may well dismiss the Lincoln as an overpriced Ford. But people who love the Lincoln’s looks, and value smoothness over sport, may prefer to call the MKX a bargain Lexus. Next Article in Automobiles (2 of 41) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Campaign Briefing | Recalls: An Alert For Agent Cool Blue Toyota Deepens Discounts on Its New Pickup With Top-Selling Silverado, G.M. Sales Defied Trend and Rose for Month BEHIND THE WHEEL/2007 Ford Edge; More Weighty Than Edgy Utility Vehicles and Other Light Trucks Next Article in Automobiles (2 of 41) &#x00bb; The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics Mark Messier Signed Puck N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
