http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/18/automobiles/18auto.html	G.M. Says It Will Make More Vehicles and Buy More Parts in India - New York Times G.M. Says It Will Make More Vehicles and Buy More Parts in India Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: April 18, 2007 NEW DELHI, April 17 — has big plans in India. Skip to next paragraph Rick Wagoner, chief executive of General Motors, announced Tuesday in New Delhi that the company would sell the Chevrolet Spark in India. In a visit to New Delhi on Tuesday, G.M.’s chief executive, Rick Wagoner, hailed the country’s thrifty manufacturing culture and growing car market and said the company would significantly increase purchasing and production here. In an interview, Mr. Wagoner said that G.M. planned to create a “local base” in India, a move that he said would not affect United States jobs. The company also introduced a new model into the Indian market on Tuesday, a compact hatchback priced at about $7,400. Car sales in India are growing about 15 percent a year, a rate projected to continue for the next five years, with low-cost cars making up the bulk of the sales. G.M. and other big automakers, hoping to offset slumping North American operations, are increasingly looking to India. In the past, the country has generally taken a back seat to China, but a growing middle class and new manufacturing prowess have made India popular for joint ventures and investments. G.M. expects India to be the second-fastest-growing car market in the world, after China, over the next 10 years. “It’s time to redouble our efforts on our manufacturing and market presence here,” Mr. Wagoner told government ministers and auto industry executives in a conference on the Indian auto industry. Mr. Wagoner said G.M. planned to take advantage of India’s high-quality, low-cost supply base “to source more parts out of India.” In a statement issued after his presentation, Mr. Wagoner said the sourcing increase could be “as much as fivefold over the next two years.” Analysts said that might translate into G.M.’s buying as much as $1 billion worth of car parts in India annually, which would be the most spent by a foreign automaker in India. In a brief interview after the conference, Mr. Wagoner said that the increased sourcing of car parts from India would not affect United States jobs because the components in question are not made in America. He would not specify which parts would come from India in the future. Given the growth of G.M.’s manufacturing in Asia, a company base in India would provide new opportunities for Indian suppliers, he said, Indian manufacturing costs are already “extremely competitive and among the lowest in the world,” Mr. Wagoner said during the conference. That is “not just due to lower wage rates,” he said. “It is also a function of the Indian mentality that abhors waste — because people cannot afford to throw things away.” Mr. Wagoner said G.M. would more than double its production capacity in India, to 225,000 vehicles a year, by making more vehicles at its Halol factory in the state of Gujarat and building a new plant in Talegaon, Maharashtra, both in western India. India has been trying to become Asia’s low-cost car manufacturing center, offering tax breaks and other incentives. Renault and Nissan announced plans in January to work with an Indian company to build a new car plant. Local analysts and manufacturing executives say India has a quality advantage over China. “The Chinese are known to manufacture very cheap cars, but the problem is that safety and emission norms are something they don’t meet,” said Kapil Singh, an auto analyst with Brics Securities, a brokerage house in Mumbai. Indian standards are as good as any in the world, he said. G.M.’s North American operations lost $4.6 billion in 2006, including about $3.8 billion that it spent on buyouts and other one-time items. Profit margins are also weakening in China, G.M.’s second-largest market, as competition lowers car prices. The new car G.M. will sell in India, the Chevrolet Spark, will be its smallest car in India. The other two G.M. models there cost significantly more, and sales are sluggish. “G.M. has a long way to go in India,” said Mr. Singh. “They haven’t been in the mainstream car business yet.” Next Article in Automobiles (30 of 41) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. G.M. Says It Will Make More Vehicles and Buy More Parts in India G.M. Plans Shift to Small Cars for the Emerging World World Business Briefing | Asia: India: G.M. Opens A Lab World Business Briefing | Asia: India: Murdoch Seeks Software Stake Find New Cars » Find Used Cars » Explore Collectible Cars » Sell Your Car » The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics Obey The Law, 1948 N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
