http://www.nytimes.com/pages/automobiles/index.html	Buy, Sell or Research a New or Used Car – New York Times MDX: If It Looks Like a Duck... Begging to be noticed. With the second-generation MDX, Acura is gambling that it can change minds and buying decisions in the high end of the S.U.V. market. Graphic: The X Files: Four Luxury Crossovers MKX: Beyond the Edge Better late than never, the five-passenger MKX is the first crossover effort from Lincoln, and it is competent and quite striking. In the Desert Near Dubai, an Oasis for Drag Racing Deep in the desert, about an hour’s drive northeast of Dubai, gearheads gather to test their mettle at a complex for quarter-mile drag racing. Forget the Lamborghini. He’d Rather Drive a V-8. Ferrari Turns 60 With a Factory Sale A sale at the factory suggests surplus stacked on the loading dock or samples on a sidewalk. But when the factory is Ferrari’s, things are a bit different. Where There’s Never an Oil Shortage An annual gathering in New York features hundreds of “greasers,” people who have converted their diesel cars and trucks to run on vegetable oil. Larceny in the Carpool Lane Shareholders Give Ex-Chief the Blame for Ford Woes By RITA K. FARRELL Ford shareholders criticized every decision that the company’s executive chairman, William Clay Ford Jr., had made, except one: his choice of successor. Highway Debris, Long an Eyesore, Grows as Hazard By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN California is beginning to address the issue of deaths caused by accidents involving objects on highways. Earnhardt Drops Team Built by His Father to Become a Free Agent Nascar’s most popular driver announced that his future would not include racing for Dale Earnhardt Inc. Toyota Posts Another Record but Warns of Slowdown Toyota reported another year of record profit but signaled a slowdown in the current year because of weakness in North America and increased spending. Behind the Wheel | 2007 Toyota Tundra Going Where Toyota’s Never Gone Before With the full-sized Tundra, Toyota is finally offering a truck big and powerful enough to compete with Detroit’s marquee pickups. Slide Show: Comparing Full-Size Pickups Share and View Photo Gallery Photos of Your Collectible Car Your Car's Restoration History Other Member's Vehicle Photos and Descriptions Your Comments and Questions Be the First to Test-Drive This New Feature » : A rally for exotic sports cars in Europe turns deadly. A Rally Turns Tragic in Macedonia Dancing With the Tundra The Future of Hydrogen Seventy years after the Hindenberg disaster, the Times tested hydrogen vehicles from three manufacturers. Writer Keith Bradsher on the news, trends and the new models that were revealed at this year's show. Airstream: The Concept Travels Well Showing Off Cars With Real Curves Must-Sees at the New York Auto Show Challenge to Emissions Rule Is Set to Start Justices Say E.P.A. Has Power to Act on Harmful Gases To Mark a Cab Centennial, These Designers Look Ahead Showing Off Cars With Real Curves Medical Regimen Keeps Racers Fresh Racing to Make the Pit Stops a Little Bit Greener The Hurricanes Are Gone, but the Cars May Remain Honda Wants to Be Known for Safety Local Radio Is Cutting the Static and Going Digital, Finally Computers That Help You Handle Skids Like a Pro Stripping Down a Harley to Draw Young Riders A BMW to Ride When a Trip Is Long and Time Is Short Behind the Wheel: Certified? Yes. Satisfied? Not Always. Magna Chairman Confirms an Offer for Chrysler Obama Criticizes Automakers on Fuel Economy Wheelspin: A Season of Events for Auto Lovers G.M. Profit Down 90% From 2006 A Crossover Helps Ford, but Not Enough to Hold Its No. 2 Spot Motoring: It’s the Truth, but Not the Whole Truth Hydrogen's Second Coming: A Universe of Promise (and a Tankful of Caveats) Hydrogen's Second Coming: On the Road, Hope for a Zero-Pollution Car Hydrogen's Second Coming: At Milepost 1 on the Hydrogen Highway Hydrogen's Second Coming: In the Air, a Very Public Failure Land Rover’s Ta