http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/08/us/politics/08obama.html	Obama Criticizes Automakers on Fuel Economy - New York Times Obama Criticizes Automakers on Fuel Economy Senator Barack Obama said Monday in Detroit that he wanted to address automakers on their turf with his criticism and his proposals. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 8, 2007 DETROIT, May 7 — Senator of Illinois delivered a stern message to Detroit auto companies on Monday, saying they had done little to lessen the nation’s dependence on foreign oil and needed to improve the fuel efficiency of their vehicles. Skip to next paragraph The latest political news from around the nation. Sounding at times like a teacher scolding a lazy but promising student, Mr. Obama at the same time proposed incentives to help General Motors, Ford and Chrysler out of a lingering slump that has resulted in dozens of plant closings and the elimination of tens of thousands of jobs this decade. Appearing before a luncheon held by the Detroit Economic Club, Mr. Obama, a Democratic presidential candidate, received a standing ovation when he was introduced by Mayor Kwame M. Kilpatrick, and again at the close of his remarks, which were broadcast live by local television stations. Mr. Obama, making his first campaign visit to Michigan, said he wanted to be blunt with Detroit auto companies on their home turf. Chief executives of the auto companies were not in attendance. “I’m making this proposal here today because I don’t believe in making proposals in California and giving a different speech in Michigan,” he said. His goal “is not to destroy the industry, but to help bring it into the 21st century,” he said. Under Mr. Obama’s plan, which he said would save 2.5 million barrels of oil a day, he proposed a 4 percent a year increase in fuel economy standards beginning in 2009, or the equivalent of about one mile per gallon per year. By 2022, the fuel economy standard for both cars and light trucks would be 40 miles per gallon, according to the plan. The Bush administration has proposed a similar method to raise the fuel economy standard over the next few years. The current federal standards are 27.5 miles per gallon for cars and 24 miles per gallon for light trucks. While the American standard for cars has not increased in the last 20 years, both China and Japan have higher standards, Mr. Obama said. He maintained that cars in Japan typically achieved the equivalent of 45 miles per gallon. In fact, the average fuel economy in 2006 for cars sold by all manufacturers in the United States was slightly more than 30 miles per gallon, higher than the federal standard requires. But automakers’ overall fuel economy was 24.2 miles per gallon, because light trucks, including S.U.V.’s, pickups and minivans, account for slightly more than half the vehicles sold in the United States. The discussion over the standards accelerated last month, when the Supreme Court ruled that the had the ability to regulate carbon dioxide emissions. The primary way to do so, experts say, is by raising fuel efficiency. Mr. Obama also proposed that fuel efficiency standards for cars be rewritten so that mileage requirements are set according to vehicle size, rather than one sweeping standard for all sizes of cars. The current method benefits Japanese auto companies, whose lineups are not as varied as their Detroit rivals, said Mr. Obama, whose state is home to a Ford assembly plant, as well as one owned by the Japanese automaker Mitsubishi. National Highway Traffic Safety Administration took a similar step this decade in recalculating the fuel economy standard for light trucks. Detroit auto companies have backed that as an option for recalculating fuel economy standards for cars. As a carrot to the industry, Mr. Obama would provide up to $3 billion to Detroit auto companies and their suppliers to retool factories to produce more fuel-efficient vehicles. If the companies invest in these vehicles, Mr. Obama also would offer the Detroit companies assistance in dealing with their burden of paying for current and retired workers’ health care expenses, estimated at $1,500 per vehicle. But a spokesman for G.M., Greg Martin, said the automaker preferred to see a broader approach to soaring health care costs. “Health care is an issue that should be a national priority and not an issue unique to G.M.,” Mr. Martin said. Despite Mr. Obama’s sometimes harsh words Monday, the diverse audience interrupted him 10 times for applause. “I think it took a lot of courage to come to Detroit and lay it on the line,” said Peter Eckstein, a retired labor union economist from Ann Arbor, Mich. Leonard Mungo, a Detroit lawyer, said he was surprised to hear specific proposals for addressing the industry’s problems. “He’s saying, ‘You got yourselves into this mess, but now this is how we get out,’ ” Mr. Mungo said. Nick Bunkley contributed reporting. More Articles in National &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Presidential Election of 2008 More Articles in National &#x00bb; The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics Men's Denim Authentic Pigment-Dyed Box Hood N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
