http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/22/automobiles/22BLUETOOTH.html	Bluetooth Plays Matchmaker: M3, Meet MP3 - New York Times Bluetooth Plays Matchmaker: M3, Meet MP3 Sign In to E-Mail or Save This By JOHN R. QUAIN Published: April 22, 2007 FEW people get behind the wheel alone anymore. Many drivers wouldn’t dare pull away from the curb without their cellphone, iPod or P.D.A. — mobile devices essential to life on the move, though not necessarily designed for use in cars. Skip to next paragraph Getting Connected Without Plugging In Smarter Lights, Minus the Blues To make the devices better, less distracting driving companions, more carmakers and electronics companies are using Bluetooth technology, which wirelessly connects phones to a headset or to the car’s sound system. Bluetooth is becoming the wireless standard in vehicles, and it has ambitions far beyond hands-free cellphone use. The benefit of Bluetooth is that it frees the hands of a driver talking on the phone, though it does not address the larger problem of diverted attention while holding a conversation. It allows users to leave a Bluetooth-equipped cellphone in a pocket or purse and still make and receive phone calls, either with a cordless headset or by using speakers and a microphone built into the vehicle. In addition, the voice-activated dialing with today’s cellphones can be used through a microphone in the car’s headliner with the driver’s hands on the wheel. One inspiration to use wireless Bluetooth devices in cars was the enactment of hands-free cellphone laws across the country. “The laws did help with the visibility and awareness of Bluetooth,” said Mike Foley, executive director of the Bluetooth Special Interest Group, a nonprofit trade group. California, Connecticut, New Jersey, New York and Washington, D.C., have all passed laws mandating the use of hands-free systems for cellphone calls. Municipalities from Florida to Utah have similar laws. Named for a 10th-century king credited with uniting warring factions of Denmark, Norway and Sweden, Bluetooth was designed to allow devices to communicate across distances of 30 feet or less. Today, every major cellphone maker includes this radio-frequency technology. And there is a wide variety of rechargeable Bluetooth headsets available from companies like Jabra, Logitech, Motorola, Nokia and Sony Ericsson. Many, however, are not designed strictly for motorists. When the headsets lose their power, for example, users often have to wait until they are at the office or home to recharge the device. One exception is Plantronics’s Discovery 665 Bluetooth Headset, which costs $150 and comes with a folding cigarette lighter charger. The tiny in-ear Discovery also uses a digital signal processor to reduce road and wind noise. Not everybody is comfortable driving with something stuck in their ear, so some automakers are offering Bluetooth as part of integrated systems. BMW, DaimlerChrysler, Ford, Honda, Nissan and Toyota offer Bluetooth in some models. The factory-installed systems allow drivers to take a call with the push of a button, like a speaker phone, while the system automatically mutes the car’s sound system. One notable laggard in Bluetooth adoption has been General Motors, which has favored its own wireless OnStar system. Only G.M.’s Cadillac STS has Bluetooth, but that may be about to change. G.M. “is developing Bluetooth in a wide range of products,” said Pete Barkey, a company spokesman. He declined to provide a timetable for its introduction in other models. Other carmakers and consumer electronics companies are looking to expand Bluetooth’s wireless possibilities. “The original scenario was purely hands-free operation,” said Mr. Foley, the trade group executive. “Now it’s pretty common to be able to synchronize a phone’s contacts with the car setup.” This allows drivers to dial a number simply by saying the person’s name. They can also see who’s calling on the vehicle’s stereo display. More cellphones, music players and headsets are also supporting Bluetooth’s Advanced Audio Distribution Profile (A2DP), which allows devices to play stereo music through a car’s sound system without wires. Several Samsung phones can play music this way, for example, and iPod owners can purchase adapters like the Jabra A125s. The $60 add-on plugs into the dock connector on an iPod to make the Bluetooth connection. Next Article in Automobiles (24 of 41) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. TECHNOLOGY; Bluetooth Plays Matchmaker: M3, Meet MP3 Wi-Fi Is Hitting the Road in Cars From Avis, but Technical and Legal Bumps Lie Ahead TECHNOLOGY; Real-Time Traffic Reports? Get Real TECHNOLOGY; Mayday! Some Cars Will Lose OnStar Link Bluetooth Special Interest Group Find New Cars » Find Used Cars » Explore Collectible Cars » Sell Your Car » The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics A Spin on the Ferry, 1964 N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
