http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/15/automobiles/15CURVES.html?ex=1334289600&en=3d4af6dc480f9203&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	Showing Off Cars With Real Curves - New York Times Showing Off Cars With Real Curves Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: April 15, 2007 Skip to next paragraph BEAUTIFUL classic automobiles are often called rolling sculpture, but the Phoenix Art Museum has taken that a step further with cars presented as actual sculpture in a gallery exhibition. “Curves of Steel: Streamlined Automobile Design,” which runs through June 3, shows how a fledgling sense of aerodynamics in the 1930s influenced designers to create cars that appeared to cheat the wind. Streamlining was a modernist trend, with toasters, typewriters, vacuum cleaners and even buildings designed to evoke a future of speed. “That was how we came up with the idea of looking at the streamline design of the ’30s,” Jim Ballinger, the museum’s director, said in a recent interview. “It was so pervasive in the art world. The actual science of aerodynamics was having an impact, but ultimately, it’s the stylization of that.” Working with art and automotive experts, the Arizona museum has assembled a collection of 22 automobiles, many of them landmark designs from the 1930s. Later cars in the collection show how aerodynamics developed and was used to real effect in land-speed record attempts, in racecars and in one of the most exotic supercars, the McLaren F1. The queen of the exhibition is the voluptuous 1939 Delahaye Type 165 designed by Giuseppi Figoni in what could be the pinnacle of coach-built artistry. The enormous cabriolet seems to float above the surface, surreal sexuality glistening in its gleaming red paint. The star of France’s display at the 1939 World’s Fair, its presence is no less jaw-dropping today. In the Depression-wracked 1930s, the reality was that most vehicles were boxy contraptions. But curvaceous streamlined cars like these embodied dreams of affluence. The Phoenix Art