http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/15/automobiles/autoreviews/15BLOCK.html	Review - Suzuki SX4 Wagon - New York Times High Wagon, Now in Half Pints The 2007 Suzuki SX4 wagon. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: April 15, 2007 Skip to next paragraph The SX4 sedan will be available in the fall. $15,624 base; $16,724 as tested with automatic transmission. A 2-liter in-line 4; four-speed automatic; all-wheel drive. All SX4&#8217;s have six air bags, including head-protection curtains. Antilock brakes and a tire pressure monitor are standard. Traction control and electronic stability control are available only on the SX4 Sport. The government has not crash-tested the SX4. With the automatic gearbox, the rating is 24 miles a gallon in town, 30 on the highway. Honda Fit $14,650; Nissan Versa SL $15,550; Chrysler PT Cruiser $17,620. (All similarly equipped.) AS the new wave of economical hatchbacks ripples through the American auto market, the era of lumbering sport utility vehicles already seems as kitschy as towering tailfins or butterfly-collar disco shirts. The Suzuki SX4 wagon is taking advantage of this shift by straddling a razor-thin line between the baby sport utility and the all-wheel-drive economy car. The SX4 is only 162.8 inches long, half a foot shorter than the four-door Versa and only about five inches longer than the Fit. From the outside, the SX4&#8217;s squat dimensions, tall windows and large side mirrors, which bear some resemblance to Mickey Mouse&#8217;s ears, deliver a welcome dose of cuteness, a trait not usually found in the macho realm of S.U.V.&#8217;s. But the SX4&#8217;s best party trick is its standard all-wheel-drive system. A switch on the center console has three settings: front drive, four-wheel drive (which transfers power between the front and rear axles), or a four-wheel mode that locks the center differential for very slippery situations. So has Suzuki managed to obtain the station wagon equivalent of geek-chic? When you step inside, you realize that the huggable exterior is somewhat muted by a sober cabin. Expanses of gray plastic are brightened (but only a bit) by slivers of metallic-looking plastic on the center console and gearshift knob. The dashboard layout is clear, with easy-to-read gauges and large rotary knobs for the air-conditioner. The base four-speaker AM/FM/CD/MP3 and XM-ready stereo is a cinch to master, if a little tinny-sounding when the volume is cranked up. A nine-speaker stereo, with subwoofer and six-disc, in-dash CD player, is standard on the SX4 Sport. My basic test vehicle came with a four-speed automatic in lieu of the five-speed manual, but it lacked the $300 convenience package that includes cruise control and a leather-wrapped steering wheel with integrated audio controls. (I was stuck with a thin, slippery steering wheel instead.) On a more positive note, the smooth-shifting automatic did a fine job in mixed city and highway driving. The SX4&#8217;s steering is solid and agile. But with a curb weight of nearly 3,000 pounds, acceleration is merely adequate with the 143-horsepower 4-cylinder engine. Fuel economy is also just on the right side of O.K., and an 11-gallon tank limits the range to as little as 260 miles between fill-ups. Oddly, the SX4 carries a higher mileage rating with the automatic than with the manual. A ride through Manhattan, Brooklyn and Long Island proved the comfort of the suspension and cloth seats. With the 60/40 split-folding rear seat lowered, there is a useful 54.3 cubic feet for cargo. The cabin is roomy enough for four average-size adults. Air-conditioning, power windows and power locks are standard, and the six air bags include side curtains. It is too bad, though, that traction and stability controls are available only on the pricier SX4 Sport. The SX4 wagon will be joined this fall by a sedan version, introduced recently at the New York auto show. The SX4 lacks the lofty mileage figures and nimble demeanor of some competitors. Yet as a pint-size wagon with standard all-wheel drive, a roomy interior and a price around $15,000, it has little direct competition at all. NICK KURCZEWSKI Next Article in Automobiles (31 of 41) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. AROUND THE BLOCK; High Wagon, Now in Half Pints There's Detroit and There's Trnava; Car Production Surges In Eastern Europe INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS; G.M. Raising Some Cash With Sale of Most of Suzuki Stake Lexus Tops Owner Survey For 5th Year Next Article in Automobiles (31 of 41) &#x00bb; The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics The Times/Ellis Island Legacy Keepsake N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/15/automobiles/autoreviews/15BLOCK.html	Review - Suzuki SX4 Wagon - New York Times High Wagon, Now in Half Pints The 2007 Suzuki SX4 wagon. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: April 15, 2007 Skip to next paragraph The SX4 sedan will be available in the fall. $15,624 base; $16,724 as tested with automatic transmission. A 2-liter in-line 4; four-speed automatic; all-wheel drive. All SX4&#8217;s have six air bags, including head-protection curtains. Antilock brakes and a tire pressure monitor are standard. Traction control and electronic stability control are available only on the SX4 Sport. The government has not crash-tested the SX4. With the automatic gearbox, the rating is 24 miles a gallon in town, 30 on the highway. Honda Fit $14,650; Nissan Versa SL $15,550; Chrysler PT Cruiser $17,620. (All similarly equipped.) AS the new wave of economical hatchbacks ripples through the American auto market, the era of lumbering sport utility vehicles already seems as kitschy as towering tailfins or butterfly-collar disco shirts. The Suzuki SX4 wagon is taking advantage of this shift by straddling a razor-thin line between the baby sport utility and the all-wheel-drive economy car. The SX4 is only 162.8 inches long, half a foot shorter than the four-door Versa and only about five inches longer than the Fit. From the outside, the SX4&#8217;s squat dimensions, tall windows and large side mirrors, which bear some resemblance to Mickey Mouse&#8217;s ears, deliver a welcome dose of cuteness, a trait not usually found in the macho realm of S.U.V.&#8217;s. But the SX4&#8217;s best party trick is its standard all-wheel-drive system. A switch on the center console has three settings: front drive, four-wheel drive (which transfers power between the front and rear axles), or a four-wheel mode that locks the center differential for very slippery situations. So has Suzuki managed to obtain the station wagon equivalent of geek-chic? When you step inside,