http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/02/automobiles/02auto.html	A Crossover Helps Ford, but Not Enough to Hold Its No. 2 Spot - New York Times A Crossover Helps Ford, but Not Enough to Hold Its No. 2 Spot The Ford Edge crossover vehicles, introduced late last year, sat on a dealer&#146;s lot in Detroit in February. The vehicle has failed to generate the sales that Ford&#146;s big sport utility vehicles once did. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 2, 2007 DETROIT, May 1 — Is the Edge giving Ford the edge it was hoping for? Skip to next paragraph At the very least, the new crossover vehicle is keeping sales at the Ford Motor Company from dropping even more than they already are this year, at a time when the company is pulling back on unprofitable sales to rental-car companies. Ford is meeting the expectations it set for the Edge when the vehicle went on sale in December. But the Edge is not generating the revenue of the big sport utility vehicles that once fueled Ford’s profits, and it is not drawing the new customers that the company will need to bounce back from its worst loss in history — $12.7 billion last year. Ford’s falling sales have allowed the Toyota Motor Corporation of Japan to replace it as the second-largest seller of vehicles in the United States, after General Motors, through the first four months. And there is the question of buzz: Ford has pulled out all the stops to promote the Edge, with television ads directed by the playwright David Mamet in its latest attempt to get attention for the vehicle. Yet there are already lease deals available for the Edge, and some Ford insiders are concerned that its price, which starts at $25,995, is too high to sustain current sales levels once the vehicle’s novelty wears off — further proof that in today’s ultra-competitive car market, automakers have only a brief window to make a splash. Since arriving at dealerships in December, the Edge has been one of the few bright spots for Ford. On Tuesday, when automakers reported sales for April, Ford said its overall sales in April fell 7 percent on a selling-day adjusted basis; a distinction made because a year ago, there were two more selling days in April. Without the Edge and two other new crossovers in its lineup, Ford’s decline last month would have been 12 percent, the worst among major automakers. Ford has sold 33,600 units of the Edge so far this year, on pace for its goal of selling 100,000 units in all of 2007. But the company’s chief sales analyst, George Pipas, said many of those had been bought by people who already owned Fords. “The products that are most traded in are other Ford products,” Mr. Pipas said. “It’s retaining Ford buyers who were in traditional S.U.V.’s that are moving into another category.” To be sure, Ford needed vehicles that could keep its customers from defecting to other brands, particularly as high gasoline prices lead consumers to seek more fuel-efficient vehicles. But the Edge alone can do little to help Ford reach its goal of earning a profit in North America by 2009. “Crossovers are not the cash cows that the Ford Explorers and Expeditions were,” said Ron Pinelli, president of the Autodata Corporation, the industry research company based in Woodcliff Lake, N.J. “There’s just not enough volume there for Ford to make up for what they’ve lost,” Mr. Pinelli said. “Even if the Edge is doing incredibly well, the profit contribution isn’t going to be terrific, and there aren’t going to be enough of them to move the scale from the loss side to the profit side.” The Edge was not enough to stop Ford’s market share from falling to 17 percent from 18 percent a year ago, according to Autodata; the decline was the largest among all major automakers. G.M.’s market share slipped to 23 percent from 23.5 percent, while the Chrysler Group had a rare increase, to 14.4 percent from 13.1 percent. Toyota leads all automakers in worldwide sales. Chrysler, which could be sold in the coming months by its German parent, DaimlerChrysler, surprised analysts by saying its April sales rose 10 percent. Chrysler executives attributed the gain to a well-organized incentive program, including free DVD players in its minivans and discounts on the Dodge Ram pickup, as well as a successful 96-hour sale at the end of the month. “We were just very fortunate to catch the wind when we did in April,” said Steven J. Landry, Chrysler’s executive vice president for North American sales and global marketing. “We had a very strong close.” Meanwhile, Japanese automakers had an uncharacteristically weak month, with Honda’s sales down 1.6 percent and Nissan’s down 11.2 percent. Toyota posted a 3.7 percent sales increase, its lowest year-over-year gain since August 2004. Although Ford came in slightly ahead of it for the month, Toyota has sold nearly 5,000 more vehicles than Ford so far this year. Yet there are signs of some bumps in the road for Toyota, like an inventory that has grown 30 percent in the last year. Many of those unsold vehicles may be the new Tundra pickups; Toyota has sold about 43,000 Tundras since the truck went on sale in February, well below the pace needed to reach its goal of selling 200,000 this year. But because the Tundra makes more money for Toyota than the Edge does for Ford, the Edge cannot necessarily be called the more successful of the two. Still, Ford and its dealers say they are thrilled with the Edge. Mr. Pipas of Ford said it was competing well against crossover models from Toyota, Honda and Nissan. “The sales levels, really coming from having no brand recognition, are kind of in the same sandbox as three really great products that have established themselves over the course of several years,” Mr. Pipas said. “I don’t know if I thought we could get there that soon.” Ron Christiano, general manager of Cortese Ford in Rochester, said customers liked the Edge because it used less gas than an S.U.V. The Edge increased traffic to the dealership more quickly than Ford’s Fusion sedan, which has sold well since its introduction in 2005, he said. Correction: May 4, 2007 A picture in the auto sales chart in Business Day on Wednesday was published in error. It showed a Nissan Altima Coupe, which is not on the market yet, rather than the Altima sedan, which had a 12.4 percent drop in sales in April. (The error first occurred in the sales chart on Jan. 4.) Next Article in Automobiles (14 of 41) &#x00bb; Get home delivery of The Times for as low as $2.99 a week — that’s 50% off. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Ford Cut Loss In Quarter; U.S. Sales Fell Ford Chief Sticking to His Road Map for Turnaround Asia's Automakers Show Sizable March Sales Gains With Top-Selling Silverado, G.M. Sales Defied Trend and Rose for Month Find New Cars » Find Used Cars » Explore Collectible Cars » Sell Your Car » The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics BECOMING JUSTICE BLACKMUN Paperback Edition N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
