http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/19/automobiles/19volkswagen.html?ex=1334635200&en=8235a29516d799dd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	With Job Cuts Continuing, Earnings More Than Double at Volkswagen - New York Times With Job Cuts Continuing, Earnings More Than Double at Volkswagen Sign In to E-Mail or Save This By THE ASSOCIATED PRESS Published: April 19, 2007 FRANKFURT, April 18 (AP) — Volkswagen, Europe’s biggest carmaker, said Wednesday that its first-quarter net profit more than doubled on solid global sales gains. In a preliminary earnings report released a day ahead of its annual shareholder meeting, Volkswagen said it earned 740 million euros (slightly more than $1 billion) in the quarter, compared with 327 million euros a year earlier. Sales rose 5.1 percent, to 26.6 billion euros ($36.1 billion), from 25.3 billion euros. Operating earnings, which analysts use as a yardstick of a company’s health, rose 80 percent, to 1.08 billion euros ($1.5 billion), from 599 million euros. VW has spent nearly two years cutting 20,000 jobs from its German work force as it faces rising European and Asian competition. The company said this week that worldwide vehicle sales rose 7.9 percent in the first quarter, to 1.47 million units. Big gains in China and Eastern Europe, and a modest gain in the United States, helped offset a dip in domestic sales after Germany increased its value-added tax rate in January. VW, based in the northern city of Wolfsburg, said it expected its operating profit for all of 2007 to “probably be higher than the previous year’s operating profit” of two billion euros. In trading here Wednesday, Volkswagen shares closed up 0.6 percent, at 115.22 euros ($156.47). Last month, Porsche raised its stake in Volkswagen to 31 percent, a move it said was aimed at protecting the company from a hostile takeover. Porsche has built up its holding to become VW’s largest shareholder. A German state, Lower Saxony, owns nearly 20 percent. Next Article in Automobiles (29 of 