http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/29/automobiles/29HINDEN.html?ex=1335499200&en=acdbd204f3df0ab5&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	In the Air, a Very Public Failure - New York Times In the Air, a Very Public Failure Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: April 29, 2007 Skip to next paragraph That&#146;s all it took to bring the Hindenburg down. Dith Pran/The New York Times Rick Zitarosa cites a hydrogen leak. The New York Times Hindenburg, three times as long as a Boeing 747, being prepared in Germany for its first test flight in 1936. It was destroyed the next year on its 63rd flight. THE May 6, 1937, crash of the Hindenburg at the Navy base here was the 20th century&#8217;s first transportation disaster captured by newsreel, audio recordings and still photos. The advancement in communications, combined with the observations of more than a thousand witnesses and survivors, is why one calamity with a relatively modest death toll permanently soiled hydrogen&#8217;s reputation. In 34 fiery seconds, hydrogen leaped from the No. 1 position on the periodic table of elements to the last thing any citizen would consider pumping into a car&#8217;s fuel tank. But was hydrogen really to blame? Over the last seven decades, countless inquiries, investigations, books, movies, television reports and Internet postings have attempted to answer that question. After weighing the evidence, Rick Zitarosa, 45, of Point Pleasant, N.J., said he thought he knew the cause of the Hindenburg&#8217;s demise. Mr. Zitarosa, a supervisor for the New Jersey Turnpike Authority , is not a scientist, engineer or lawyer. But since he read a book on the subject as a 10-year old, his passion has been the study of airships in general and the Hindenburg in particular. His colleague, Lawrence Lyford, deputy public affairs officer for the Naval Air Engineering Station here, said, &#8220;Rick Zitarosa is our resident expert on the subject of lighter-than-air service. He achieved this standing through extensive document research and numerous interviews.&#8221; Mr. Zitarosa said the ship, the German zeppelin LZ 129, was on its 63rd flight and had logged 3,000 hours of reliable service. &#8220;It was a large, complex machine, three times as long as a Boeing 747,&#8221; he said. &#8220;Its structure consisted of 12 miles of duralumin, an aircraft alloy, girders joined by over 4 million rivets and 100 miles of brace wires. The outer skin was 40 acres of cotton fabric impregnated with iron oxide, cellulose acetate butyrate and aluminum powder.&#8221; He added that the zeppelin&#8217;s 16 cells, made of gas-proof latex-treated cotton, contained seven million cubic feet of hydrogen gas capable of lifting 247,000 pounds. Four Daimler-Benz diesel engines propelled the Hindenburg to a maximum speed of 84 miles an hour. &#8220;A crew of 16 operated the ship and there were cabins inside the hull for 50 passengers,&#8221; he said. On May 6, strong Atlantic headwinds and stormy weather on the East Coast had delayed the Hindenburg&#8217;s arrival by 12 hours. Mr. Zitarosa said that Captain Max Pruss &#8220;may have been in a hurry to get the ship on the ground. During a lull in the thunderstorm activity, he made a rather tight turn during its final approach. Gas was vented to bring the ship into trim. During the last 11 minutes of the trip, the ship was tail heavy, so 2,000 pounds of water was dropped from the stern. &#8220;Electrical conditions in the atmosphere were probably a little risky. Earlier in the day, rubber factories in northern New Jersey had been closed due to static in the air; the fear was that stocks of carbon black might ignite.&#8221; The Hindenburg&#8217;s heavy tail just before landing is evidence of a loss of hydrogen, Mr. Zitarosa said, adding that there were two likely explanations for the leak: a stuck valve during maneuvering to reduce altitude or a minor structural failure caused by guy wires snapping during the aggressive turn, resulting in the puncture of a gas cell. &#8220;U.S. Navy Chief Petty Officer R. H. Ward, from his position at the top of the mooring mast, noticed fluttering in the upper-rear area of the Hindenburg&#8217;s skin,&#8221; Mr. Zitarosa said. &#8220;That had to be gas rippling in the space between the frame and the outer covering.&#8221; Another witness saw a likely ignition source. Mr. Zitarosa said a Princeton professor reported seeing a dim blue flame, like St. Elmo&#8217;s fire, the electrical discharge that sometimes occurs during thunderstorms, flickering along the ship&#8217;s backbone girder. The ship burst into flame at about 7:25 p.m. &#8220;In a nutshell, the catastrophe began with escaping hydrogen,&#8221; he said. &#8220;Air mixing with the hydrogen created a combustible mixture. Either a spark jumping from the electrically charged outer covering to the metal framework or the St. Elmo&#8217;s fire lit the mixture. A puff or pop indicating detonation was heard by several observers. &#8220;It&#8217;s important to note that the Hindenburg didn&#8217;t explode. It was consumed by rapid combustion; this is evident in photographs. Heat produced in the first burning cell raised the temperature of adjacent cells, causing hydrogen to spill out of pressure-relief valves. It took only 34 seconds for fire to engulf the entire ship.&#8221; Thirty-six people were killed. What about several sabotage theories that have been debated? &#8220;Germany had many enemies in 1937,&#8221; Mr. Zitarosa said. &#8220;After the disaster, there were thorough investigations by a very paranoid Nazi government and its notorious secret police, but no smoking gun was found.&#8221; Theorists have also pointed to hot diesel engines, leaking diesel fuel, and skin allegedly coated with rocket fuel as the cause of the accident. Mr. Zitarosa dismissed that theory, saying that the engines and fuel were in the lower half of the ship, while the fire was observed first in the upper part. Mr. Zitarosa also dismissed the incendiary paint theory proposed by a retired technician, Addison Bain, and an author, R. G. Van Treuren. The Discovery Channel&#8217;s &#8220;Mythbuster&#8221; television show rejected the paint theory after igniting three scale-model Hindenburgs. While the accident destroyed the Hindenburg, it didn&#8217;t harm the base. Seventy years later, Lakehurst is still a Navy facility. Before the Navy came to town, the property was used for World War I chemical warfare experimentation by the Army. In 1919, Navy Secretary converted the site to a Navy dirigible field to be equipped with two rigid airship hangars. Hangar No. 1, still standing, was completed two years later. The Navy commissioned rigid airships for use as long-range aerial scouts and nonrigid ships (called blimps) for training and antisubmarine work. All were filled with helium, not hydrogen. After World War II, training and maintenance continued until 1962. This year, the Navy acquired a commercial blimp that it is testing at Lakehurst. Now called Naval Air Engineering Station, Lakehurst specializes in producing aircraft carrier launch, recovery, and support equipment for planes and helicopters. Don Sherman, technical editor of Automobile magazine, is a frequent contributor to The New York Times. Next Article in Automobiles (19 of 41) &#x00bb; Want to save this article?  Download the Times File Toolbar - get it now with TimesSelect. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. HYDROGEN'S SECOND COMING; In the Air, a Very Public Failure LOSS OF THE SHUTTLE: INSULATION; NASA Was Told in 1990 About Vulnerable Tiles Leak at Indian Point 2 Plant Leads It to Curtail Operations Fuel Leak Delays Launching of Space Shuttle Find New Cars » Find Used Cars » Explore Collectible Cars » Sell Your Car » The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny The Curious Cook: The Five-Second Rule Explored, or How Dirty Is That Bologna? The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks Highway Debris, Long an Eyesore, Grows as Hazard New York City Renters Cope With Squeeze Psychiatrists, Children and Drug Industry&#8217;s Role The Critical Years: Middle School Manages Distractions of Adolescence Genes Take Charge, and Diets Fall by the Wayside Fisher Is a Father First, and a Jazz Player Later Your Money: A Contrarian on Retirement Says Wait Go to Complete List » Giuliani to Support Abortion Rights G.O.P. Moderates Warn Bush Iraq Must Show Gains Bush in Accord With Democrats on Trade Deals President Open to Benchmarks in Iraq Measure Gonzales Seems Confident He Will Stay, Officials Say Facebook to Offer Free Classifieds Role of F.B.I. Informer Draws Praise and Questions On Carrier in Gulf, Cheney Issues Warning to Iran Romney Works to Put Skeptics' Doubts to Rest Go to Complete List » Go to Complete List » The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
